  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I am a 13-year-old boy that wants to learn how to program video games. What programming languages should I learn? How do I get started?",
  "response": "That's awesome that you want to learn how to program video games! Starting at 13 is a great age to dive into programming because you\u2019ll have plenty of time to practice and improve. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you get started:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Learn the Basics of Programming**\nBefore jumping into game development, it\u2019s helpful to understand the fundamentals of programming. Start with beginner-friendly languages:\n\n- **Python**: Python is easy to learn and widely used. It\u2019s a great first language to understand concepts like variables, loops, and functions. You can also use Python to create simple games (e.g., with the Pygame library).\n- **JavaScript**: If you\u2019re interested in web-based games or interactive apps, JavaScript is a good choice. You can use it with HTML5 to create browser games.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Learn a Game Development Language or Engine**\nOnce you\u2019re comfortable with programming basics, you can move on to languages or tools specifically designed for game development:\n\n- **C# with Unity**: Unity is one of the most popular game engines, and it uses C#. Unity is great for 2D and 3D games and has tons of tutorials and resources for beginners.\n- **GDScript with Godot**: Godot is a free and open-source game engine that uses GDScript (a language similar to Python). It\u2019s beginner-friendly and perfect for 2D games.\n- **C++ with Unreal Engine**: Unreal Engine is a powerful engine for creating high-quality 3D games. It uses C++, which is more advanced but worth learning if you\u2019re serious about game development.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Start Small**\nBegin with simple projects to build your skills:\n- Create a basic 2D game like Pong, Snake, or Flappy Bird.\n- Experiment with game mechanics like movement, collision detection, and scoring.\n- Gradually add more features as you get comfortable.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Use Online Resources**\nThere are many free and paid resources to help you learn:\n- **YouTube Tutorials**: Channels like Brackeys, Code Monkey, and The Cherno have great game dev tutorials.\n- **Online Courses**: Websites like Udemy, Coursera, and Codecademy often have beginner-friendly game development courses.\n- **Documentation**: Learn to read the official documentation for Unity, Godot, or the engine you choose.\n- **Communities**: Join forums like Reddit\u2019s r/gamedev, Discord servers, or game development communities to ask questions and share your progress.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Practice and Experiment**\nThe best way to learn is by doing:\n- Work on small projects to test your skills.\n- Experiment with different game genres (e.g., platformers, puzzle games, RPGs).\n- Don\u2019t be afraid to make mistakes\u2014learning from them is part of the process!\n\n---\n\n### **6. Build a Portfolio**\nAs you create more games, save your projects in a portfolio. This can be a website, GitHub repository, or even a YouTube channel where you show off your work. It\u2019s a great way to track your progress and share your skills with others.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Stay Motivated**\nGame development can be challenging, but it\u2019s also incredibly rewarding. Celebrate your successes, and don\u2019t give up if things get tough. Keep learning, and you\u2019ll improve over time.\n\n---\n\n### **Recommended Starting Point**\nIf you\u2019re brand new to programming, start with Python and Pygame to create simple 2D games. Once you\u2019re comfortable, learn Unity and C# for more advanced projects.\n\nGood luck on your game development journey! Have fun and keep creating! \ud83c\udfae\ud83d\ude80",
  "temperature": 1.0,
